\section{Motivation}

MRX relaxes a magnetic field $\mathbf{B}$ toward an MHD equilibrium by evolving a fictitious--time dynamics
\[
  \partial_t \mathbf{B} = - \nabla \times (\mathbf{v} \times \mathbf{B}),
\]
where the velocity $\mathbf{v}$ is chosen to reduce a magnetic energy functional subject to constraints such as $\nabla\!\cdot\mathbf{B}=0$ and (optionally) force--free conditions.
In the simplest implementation, the update direction at each step is a deterministic function of the current state (a projected Lorentz force or a quasi--Newton step).

However, the discrete energy landscape in a high--dimensional configuration space can exhibit multiple local minima, flat directions, or nearly marginal barriers associated with island formation and onset of stochastic field lines.
To better explore this landscape and to probe the robustness of equilibria, MRX includes an option to add \emph{stochastic, divergence--free noise} to the update direction.

\section{Noise model in the time stepper}

Let $\mathbf{u}$ denote the deterministic update direction at a given pseudo--time step (for example, a projected Lorentz force or a quasi--Newton direction). The MRX time stepper defines an energy--weighted norm using the mass matrix $M_2$ on the 2--form space:
\[
  \|\mathbf{u}\|_2 = \bigl(\mathbf{u}^T M_2\,\mathbf{u}\bigr)^{1/2}.
\]

When the \verb|stochastic| flag is enabled, the actual update direction is modified to
\[
  \mathbf{u}_{\text{stoch}} = \mathbf{u} + \alpha\,\boldsymbol{\xi}_{\mathrm{df}},
\]
where:
\begin{itemize}
  \item $\boldsymbol{\xi}_{\mathrm{df}}$ is a divergence--free Gaussian random field constructed from i.i.d.~samples $\boldsymbol{\xi} \sim \mathcal{N}(0, I)$ by solving
  \[
    \tilde{\boldsymbol{\xi}} = M_2^{-1} \boldsymbol{\xi}, \qquad
    \boldsymbol{\xi}_{\mathrm{df}} = P_{\mathrm{Leray}}\,\tilde{\boldsymbol{\xi}},
  \]
  with $P_{\mathrm{Leray}}$ the discrete Leray projector enforcing $\nabla\!\cdot\mathbf{B}=0$;
  \item the scalar amplitude $\alpha$ is set by a \emph{noise level}
  \[
    \alpha = \texttt{noise\_level} \times \|\mathbf{u}\|_2,
  \]
  where \verb|noise_level| is stored in the relaxation state and updated each outer iteration by a user--supplied schedule.
\end{itemize}
The resulting step
\[
  \mathbf{B}_{n+1} = \mathbf{B}_n - \Delta t\,\mathbf{u}_{\text{stoch}}
\]
remains divergence--free by construction while introducing controlled random perturbations to the direction of downhill motion.

\section{Benefits for equilibrium searches}

\subsection{Escaping shallow local minima}

In a purely deterministic scheme, the relaxation may become trapped in a shallow local minimum or stall in a nearly flat valley of the discrete energy functional.
The stochastic term effectively turns the gradient--based search into a \emph{noisy} descent, analogous to simulated annealing:
\begin{itemize}
  \item The deterministic part moves downhill in energy.
  \item The divergence--free noise perturbs the direction within the admissible subspace without violating $\nabla\!\cdot\mathbf{B}=0$.
\end{itemize}
With a moderate initial noise level and a decaying schedule, one can:
\begin{itemize}
  \item explore multiple nearby basins of attraction early in the run,
  \item then gradually reduce the noise so that the solution settles into a \emph{deeper} or more robust equilibrium than would be obtained by deterministic relaxation alone.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Sampling a family of nearby equilibria}

For configurations with marginal modes or weakly broken symmetries, there may be a family of nearby equilibria related by small changes in island structures or stochastic layers.
Running the relaxation multiple times with different random seeds and a fixed noise schedule generates an ensemble of slightly different final states:
\begin{itemize}
  \item This ensemble can be used to estimate the \emph{spread} in quantities such as rotational transform, Shafranov shift, or island widths.
  \item It provides a more realistic view of equilibrium sensitivity than a single deterministic run.
\end{itemize}

\section{Benefits for stability and stochasticity diagnostics}

The impact of stochastic noise is particularly informative when combined with field--line tracing and stability proxies:
\begin{itemize}
  \item \textbf{Field-line stochasticity:} Small divergence--free perturbations to $\mathbf{B}$ can seed or enhance stochastic layers. Comparing Poincar\'e plots from deterministic and stochastic runs highlights how easily field lines become chaotic, which is relevant for transport.
  \item \textbf{Robustness to perturbations:} If an equilibrium remains qualitatively unchanged (e.g.\ similar island structure, comparable force residuals) under multiple noisy relaxations, this suggests a robust basin of attraction. Large variability indicates sensitivity to perturbations that may correlate with poor stability margins.
  \item \textbf{Current density structure:} Stochastic relaxations can reveal how localized current channels or edge currents respond to small perturbations, indicating whether sharp features are physically meaningful or artefacts of a particular deterministic path.
\end{itemize}

\section{Demonstrating improvements in practice}

To \emph{show} the benefits of stochastic noise in MRX, one can perform paired experiments:
\begin{enumerate}
  \item Choose a configuration script (e.g.\ a stellarator relaxation from NFS data) and a base resolution.
  \item Run a \textbf{deterministic} relaxation with \verb|noise.max = 0| and record:
  \begin{itemize}
    \item force norm vs iteration,
    \item magnetic energy vs iteration,
    \item final Poincar\'e plots and axis trajectories,
    \item current density profiles.
  \end{itemize}
  \item Run a \textbf{stochastic} relaxation with a moderate initial noise level, e.g.\ \verb|noise.max = 0.05| and a \verb|tanh| or linear schedule that decays to zero over the outer iterations.
  \item Repeat the stochastic run with several different random keys to obtain an ensemble of final states.
\end{enumerate}
The improvements and qualitative differences can then be documented as:
\begin{itemize}
  \item \textbf{Convergence behavior:} in some cases the stochastic runs continue to reduce the force norm after the deterministic run has stalled, or reach a lower final energy.
  \item \textbf{Equilibrium quality:} Poincar\'e sections may exhibit cleaner island chains or better-preserved symmetry in the stochastic runs, indicating that the deterministic path had become trapped in a less regular configuration.
  \item \textbf{Sensitivity analysis:} the spread across stochastic realizations provides error bars on equilibrium quantities, illustrating stability or fragility of a given configuration.
\end{itemize}

\section{Recommendations}

\begin{itemize}
  \item Use \textbf{small} noise levels (e.g.\ $10^{-3}$--$10^{-1}$ relative to $\|\mathbf{u}\|_2$) and decaying schedules to avoid overwhelming the deterministic descent.
  \item Enable stochastic noise primarily in phases where exploration is desired (early in the relaxation), and reduce it as the force residual approaches the desired tolerance.
  \item For quantitative comparisons to other equilibrium codes, always report whether stochastic noise was used and, if so, summarize the noise schedule and the spread across multiple realizations.
\end{itemize}

